    description: "How BDH neurons become dedicated, interpretable feature detectors",
    icon: "",
    lessons: [
      {
        id: "monosemanticity-theory",
        title: "The Superposition Catastrophe",
        slug: "monosemanticity-theory",
        estimatedMinutes: 10,
        sections: [
          {
            type: "text",
            content: `**Polysemanticity** is the original sin of dense neural networks. Because Transformers have far fewer neurons than there are concepts in the world (d_model ≪ M), they are mathematically forced to store multiple unrelated concepts in the same neuron — **vector superposition**.

The result: a neuron firing for both "cats" and "geometry". This makes the model a black box.`
          },
          {
            type: "callout",
            variant: "warning",
            title: "The Superposition Catastrophe",
            content: "In standard Transformers (using GeLU), FFN(x) = GeLU(xW₁)W₂ allows unrestricted activations in ℝ. A neuron can encode feature A as positive, feature B as negative, and pack them both in — invisible to inspection."
          },
          {
            type: "formula",
            label: "Hebbian Weight Update Rule",
            latex: "\\Delta W_{ij} \\propto (x_i \\cdot x_j) - \\gamma W_{ij}",
            explanation: "Connections strengthen when pre-synaptic and post-synaptic neurons fire together (xi·xj), and decay via -γWij when they don't. Orthogonal concepts (near-zero correlation) naturally separate into distinct neurons."
          },
          {
            type: "text",
            content: `BDH's white-box probing of trained models revealed remarkable **Specialist Neurons**:

